title.narrative: Apoiando o ambiente de política para o desenvolvimento econômico (SPEED+)
Supporting the Policy Environment for Economic Development (SPEED+)

description.narrative: (Mozambique): .The Supporting the Policy Environment for Economic.Development (SPEED+) activity promotes an improved enabling environment to.attract investment, expand markets, and reduce costs for businesses,.contributing to the Mission Objective of inclusive economic growth while.conserving natural resources. SPEED+ provides capacity-building to the.government, private sector, and civil society to improve public-private.dialogue, strengthen the implementation of government policies and regulations,.and to support structural policy reforms across: (1) agriculture and nutrition,.(2) trade and business enabling environment, (3) power and water, and (4).biodiversity conservation. In agriculture, SPEED+ promotes an improved land.policy framework, backs government efforts to update laws governing key.agriculture sectors, promotes rural trade, and supports an improved nutrition.policy. SPEED+ helps Mozambique improve its 'Doing Business' indicators,.including efforts to update legislation, such as the Labor Law. The program.promotes implementation of the Trade Facilitation Agreement and the AGOA.Utilization Strategy. SPEED+ supports improved trade policies and government.capacities to improve competitiveness of trade corridors. SPEED+ strengthens.the legal framework and government's regulatory capacity for power generation.and distribution in tandem with improving the enabling environment for.Independent Power Producers. The program develops tools to strengthen the.licensing, monitoring, and capacity of private water systems, and stimulate.private investment in water and sanitation. SPEED+ works with government,.private sector, and civil society to strengthen biodiversity conservation.policies, provide institutional support to the National Administration of.Conservation Areas, and support effective co-management and governance of.conservation areas... .
